What is Advertised on Google in Croatia – a Visualization
tinjano.github.io

Introduction¶

This notebook deals with data about advertisements shown by Google, with data collected from the new Google Ads Transparency Center. There is multifold motivation for this project, but one is most prominent – transparency. With ever greater saturation of the digital space with advertising, it only makes sense to hold advertisers and others who profit accountable in cases where their activities may be considered dubious, shady, illegal or otherwise harmful. While most advertising contains some form of skewing of the truth in an effort to influence potential customers, in recent times there has been particular outcry over a digital ecosystem ever more populated with, to put it facetiously but simply, the kind of advertisements previously seen only on pornographic websites. Through systematic analysis of collected data about advertisements, we can in theory investigate both patterns and specific actors, thereby separating facts from talking points and painting a clear picture both for individuals and institutions.

Unfortunately, the data offered by Google's transparency center is quite lackluster. A number of parameters one would expect to see are not shown, e.g. money spent on the advertisement, audience response rates, specific criteria used for targeting (as opposed to only which categories either were or were not used) or keywords used. To expand on the latter, while an ad's contents can be seen on a given location given by an URL, it is not in any way given in the table. While the topic column is displayed, it is quite broad, with harmful content like ads promoting gambling (note later that the 6th most prominent advertiser is a gambling company) being euphemistically classified as 'hobbies, games & leisure'. Interestingly, data about the number of times that an ad was shown is available only in the EEA area with Turkey, as this is the legal requirement in exactly those areas. It is very clear that Google is doing the bare minimum not to face legal challenges, while using this bare minimum to make claims about its supposed commitments to transparency and safety. The other table, involving removed advertisements, is even more lackluster. In it, the advertiser is not shown and the contents of the advertisement cannot be seen anywhere. While the existing information can still find a use in investigating trends and patterns, very little effort towards transparency is truly made.

For exactly how the data was gathered, see the collecting-data.ipynb notebook. You can also download the dataset for yourself on Kaggle. This notebook will focus mainly on visualizations. All plots can be found within the plots/ folder.

Some Additional Cleaning¶

There are some remaining problems in the dataset:

  • sometimes advertiser names have leading spaces or a different suffix in some instances, creating seemingly different advertisers
  • some upper bounds of impression counts are 2^64-1 either due to error or to signal there is no upper bound; they will be made equal to the lower bounds
In [3]:
df.advertiser_disclosed_name = df.advertiser_disclosed_name.str.strip(' .\/\\\'\"\(\),`[]{};\n\t:')
df.times_shown_upper[df.times_shown_upper > 2 ** 50] = df.times_shown_lower
df_removed.times_shown_upper[df_removed.times_shown_upper > 2 ** 50] = df_removed.times_shown_lower

In [7]:
def piechart(ax, labels, x, k=None, **kwargs):
    """
    piechart function
    if k is set, the set is reduced to the top k categories
    and others are grouped into 'other'
    """
    if k is not None:
        labels, x = np.append(labels[:k].astype('str'), 'other'), np.append(x[:k], x[k:].sum())
    
    patches, texts, autotexts = ax.pie(labels=labels, x=x, **kwargs)
    for patch, text in zip(patches, texts):
        patch.set_edgecolor('#000')
        text.set_color(plt.rcParams['text.color'])

    return patches, texts, autotexts

Top 100 Advertisers¶

It is interesting to determine which particular advertisers are, by some definition, most influential. For this definition we will choose the total number of impressions (times that their ads were shown). Alternatives are total count of ads published or total number of active days, but these measures would overrepresent ads that were not mainly intended to be shown in Croatia, even if they were shown there as well. Another interesting measure is the number of impressions per single ad, measuring quality over quantity. Also interesting are restrictions to certain topics, formats or locations. To reduce clutter in this notebook, many of these alternatives are explored in the topk.ipynb notebook, while the plots can be found within the plots/ folder.

On a technical note, we are shortening very long official advertiser names. This can be removed in cases where it is important that the entire name is displayed.

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 20))

y = [aux.shorten(name, 40) for name in pivoted_df.index]
left = np.zeros(pivoted_df.shape[0])

# draw stacked bars
for ad_format_type in df.ad_format_type.unique():
    width = pivoted_df[ad_format_type]
    ax.barh(y=y, width=width, left=left, label=ad_format_type)
    left += width

plt.draw()

oom = vars(ax.get_xaxis().get_major_formatter()).get('orderOfMagnitude')
for i, (total, advertiser_disclosed_name, ticklabel) in enumerate(zip(pivoted_df.total, pivoted_df.index, ax.get_yticklabels())):
    # add value labels to the right of bars
    text = f'{total/10**oom:.2f}' if oom > 1 else str(total)
    ax.text(total, i, text, ha='left', va='center', size='smaller')

    # change font in case label contains Chinese/Japanese/Korean characters
    if aux.contains_cjk(ticklabel.get_text()):
        try:
            ticklabel.set_font(cjk_font_path)
        except FileNotFoundError:
            pass
        

    # place country flags before names
    location = loc_dict.get(advertiser_disclosed_name)
    try:
        abbrev = aux.country_to_abbrev.get(location).lower()
        flag_image = plt.imread(flags_path/f'{abbrev}.png')
    except (FileNotFoundError, AttributeError, KeyError):
        continue

    window_extent = ticklabel.get_window_extent().transformed(ax.transData.inverted())
    x0, y0, x1, y1 = window_extent.get_points().flatten()
    
    imh, imw = flag_image.shape[:2]
    
    zoom = (ticklabel.get_fontsize() * 0.8) / imh
    flag_offsetbox = OffsetImage(flag_image, zoom=zoom)
    
    flag_artist = AnnotationBbox(flag_offsetbox, xy=(0, 0), xybox=(x0, i), boxcoords='data', frameon=False, box_alignment=(1.1, 0.5))
    ax.add_artist(flag_artist)

# colloquialize offset label
# note: offset_label.set_text('...') or
# offset_label.get_text().set_text('...') wont work
offset_label = ax.get_xaxis().get_offset_text()
offset_label_text = offset_label.get_text()
x, y, _, _ =  offset_label.get_window_extent().get_points().flatten()
x, y = ax.transData.inverted().transform((x, y))

ax.text(x, y, aux.humanize_dict.get(offset_label_text))
ax.xaxis.offsetText.set_visible(False)

ax.set(
    title=f'Advertisers by Total # of Impressions (top {k})',

Distributions¶

There are two variables in the dataset that can be interpreted as continuous, those being days_running (nr. of days that an ad is active) and the number of impressions. Surprisingly, the correlation between the two is very close to zero (even when making some reasonable restriction), so their joint distribution is uninteresting.

With regard to the number of active days, the spike near the end of the range is likely due to the fact that many ads have still not stopped running during the relatively short time that this dataset encompasses.

The distribution of impression counts has a large but very concentrated range (the vast majority of the ads were seen 0-1000 times). The situation is more balanced when restricting ourselves only to Croatian advertisers, since there is a very large number of advertisements that may have been shown in Croatia but were mostly focused elsewhere. Note that we are using a logarithmic scale.

Trends¶

In this subsection we explore changes in certain parameters over time. We divide the dataset into weekly segments according to the first time an ads was shown (first_shown column). Note that:

  • there is a large influx of ads at the very beginning, likely due to some aspects of the table's construction by Google
  • there are very few near the end of the time range, due to the fact that we selected only ads with full information already available; thus many ads that became active very recently are not in the dataset.

Because of these two facts, we will restrict the dataset to a more suitable time interval. It would be interesting to redraw some of these graphs once a dataset with a larger timespan is available.

In [16]:
dft = df.copy()[(df.first_shown > '2023-03-05') & (df.first_shown <= '2023-11-12')]
In [17]:
time_grouper = pd.Grouper(key='first_shown', freq='w')
In [18]:
def format_axes(ax, labelsize=6, formatter=monthly_formatter, rotation=30, format_legend=True, **kwargs):
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', labelsize=labelsize)
    ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter=formatter)
    for label in ax.get_xticklabels(which='major'):
        label.set(rotation=rotation)
    ax.set(**kwargs)
    if format_legend:
        ax.legend().set_title('')

Violation Categories and Removal Reasons¶

Each removal is given one of four broad removal categories, and each is further divided into several subcategories called removal reasons. Note that some of the very rare reasons are not explicitly listed on the plot.

In [30]:
reasons_frame = (
    df_removed.groupby(['violation_category', 'removal_reason'])
    .agg(
        count_=('creative_page_url', 'count')
    )
    .reset_index()
    .sort_values(['violation_category', 'count_'], ascending=[True, False])
    .query('count_ > 0')
)

# returns True if color in rgba format is 'light'
is_light = lambda color_rgba: np.linalg.norm(color_rgba * np.array([0.299, 0.587, 0.114, 0])) > 0.5

    **pie_kwargs, rotatelabels=True, radius=2

fig.legend(handles, base_color_map.keys(), loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1, dy, 0.5, 1))

# rotate percentage labels in small slices
# & remove all labels in very small slices
# & change text color depending on background brightness
srs = reasons_frame.count_
pcts = (srs.values.cumsum() + np.roll(srs.values, 1).cumsum()) / 2 / srs.values.sum()
for pct, wedge, text, autotext in zip(pcts, wedges, texts, autotexts):
    ratio = float(autotext.get_text()[:-1]) / 100
    if ratio < 0.03 and ratio >= 0.01:
        autotext.set_size(8)
        autotext.set_rotation(pct * 360 + 180 * (0.5 < pct < 0.75))
    elif ratio < 0.01:
        text.set_text('')
        autotext.set_text('')

    if not is_light(wedge.get_facecolor()):
        autotext.set_color(plt.rcParams.get('text.color'))

Active Days Depending on Category¶

Earlier we saw that ads that are removed do often get removed relatively quickly. To be precise: 25% of removed ads will be removed within 4 days and 50% within a month (26 days is the 50th percentile). However, a different 25% percent will stay on for at least around 3 months (105 days is the 75th percentile). Here we explore how this varies across the violation categories and removal reasons.

The below plots can be redrawn with the default palette when greater visibility is needed.

    current_frame = df_removed[df_removed.violation_category == category].copy()

    value_counts_series = current_frame.removal_reason.value_counts()
    if len(value_counts_series) > k + 1:
        top_k_cats = current_frame.removal_reason.value_counts().index[:k]
        current_frame.removal_reason = current_frame.removal_reason.cat.add_categories('other')
        current_frame.loc[~current_frame.removal_reason.isin(top_k_cats), 'removal_reason'] = 'other'
        current_frame.removal_reason = current_frame.removal_reason.cat.remove_unused_categories()

    sns.kdeplot(
        data=current_frame,
        x='days_running',
        common_norm=False,
        hue='removal_reason',
        palette=sns.dark_palette(
            color=base_color_map.get(category),
            n_colors=min(k+1, len(value_counts_series)),
            reverse=True
        ),
        fill=True,
        ax=ax
    )

    ax.get_legend().set_title('')
    ax.set(xlabel='days active', ylabel='', title=f'by reason, in category \'{category}\'')

fig = plt.figure(figsize=base_dims * np.array([4, 2]))
fig.suptitle('Violations and Removal Reasons Over Time', y=1.01)

ax_main = plt.subplot2grid((2, 4), (0, 0), rowspan=2, colspan=2)

ax_sec = []
for row, col in itertools.product([0, 1], [2, 3]):
    ax_sec.append(
        plt.subplot2grid((2, 4), (row, col), 1, 1)
    )

x = dft_agg.last_shown
bottom = np.zeros(dft_agg.shape[0])
for category in base_color_map.keys():
    height = dft_agg[category].values
    ax_main.bar(x=x, height=height, bottom=bottom, width=5, label=category)
    bottom += height

format_axes(ax_main, title='by violation category', xlabel='', ylabel='count', labelsize=10)

k = 4  # for visual clarity, only display top k reasons
for ax, category in zip(ax_sec, base_color_map.keys()):
    srs = df_removed[df_removed.violation_category == category].removal_reason.value_counts()
    all_reasons = srs.index[srs.values > 0].values
    top_k_cats = srs.index.values[:k]
    # print(category, top_k_cats)
    
    current_frame = (
        dft_removed[dft_removed.violation_category == category]
        .groupby([time_grouper, 'removal_reason'])
        .agg(
            count_=('creative_page_url', 'count')
        )
        .reset_index()
        .pivot_table(
            values='count_',
            index='last_shown',
            columns='removal_reason',
            aggfunc='sum',
            fill_value=0
        )
    )
    current_frame = current_frame.loc[:, current_frame.columns.isin(all_reasons)]

    if len(current_frame.columns) - 1 > k + 1:
        current_frame['other'] = current_frame.loc[:, ~current_frame.columns.isin(top_k_cats)].sum(axis=1, numeric_only=True)
        current_frame = current_frame.loc[:, [col for col in current_frame.columns if col in top_k_cats or col == 'other']]
    
    x = current_frame.index
    bottom = np.zeros(current_frame.shape[0])
    palette = sns.dark_palette(base_color_map.get(category), int(len(current_frame.columns) * 1.6), reverse=True)[:len(current_frame.columns)]
    
    for reason, color in zip(current_frame.columns, palette):
        height = current_frame[reason].values
        ax.bar(x=x, height=height, bottom=bottom, width=5, label=reason, color=color)
        bottom += height

    ax.legend()   
    format_axes(ax, xlabel='', ylabel='count', title=f'by reason, in category \'{category}\'', labelsize=5)
